<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<html xmlns:MadCap="http://www.madcapsoftware.com/Schemas/MadCap.xsd" MadCap:lastBlockDepth="6" MadCap:lastHeight="609" MadCap:lastWidth="1165">
    <body>
        <p>Margin notes are used to place text or images in the left margin of a manual, next to the main body of the text. Margin notes do not appear in online outputs unless you explicitly link them to the text, where they will appear as popups.</p>
        <MadCap:dropDown>
            <MadCap:dropDownHead>
                <MadCap:dropDownHotspot>How to Create a Margin Note</MadCap:dropDownHotspot>
            </MadCap:dropDownHead>
            <MadCap:dropDownBody>
                <ol>
                    <li>In the Word source document, place your cursor at the point youâ€™d like to insert the margin note.</li>
                    <li>
                        <p>In the <span class="Emphasis">Doc-To-Help</span> ribbon, click the <span class="Emphasis">Margin Note</span> button and  select <span class="Emphasis">Create</span>.</p>
                        <p>A two-column table is placed in the document with the text of the paragraph in the right hand table cell. If table gridlines are turned on in Word, you'll see a dotted outline of the table. The gridlines do not print.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>Type the margin note (or insert an image) in the left column of the table. The paragraph text will be in the right column.</li>
                </ol>
                <p>If you would like to add another margin note for the same paragraph, click in the left column, select the <span class="Emphasis">Margin Note</span> button and choose <span class="Emphasis">Add Definition</span>.</p>
            </MadCap:dropDownBody>
        </MadCap:dropDown>
        <MadCap:snippetBlock src="../../../Shared/All/Print-Output/Empty-Page-Break-After.flsnp" MadCap:conditions="D2H-Guides.D2H-Documents-Templates-Content" />
        <MadCap:dropDown>
            <MadCap:dropDownHead>
                <MadCap:dropDownHotspot>How to Create a Hotlink to a Margin Note</MadCap:dropDownHotspot>
            </MadCap:dropDownHead>
            <MadCap:dropDownBody>
                <ol>
                    <li>After following the previous steps to create a margin note, highlight the text in the right column that you want to use as a hotspot.</li>
                    <li>In the <span class="Emphasis">Doc-To-Help</span> ribbon, click the <span class="Emphasis">Margin Note</span> button and select <span class="Emphasis">Set Link</span>.</li>
                    <li>
                        <p>A dialog confirms that you want to link the selected text with the contents of the highlighted cell (i.e., the margin note). If it is correct, click <span class="Emphasis">OK</span>. If not, use the  <span class="Emphasis">Previous</span> and  <span class="Emphasis">Next</span> buttons to navigate to the proper cell. </p>
                        <p>The hotspot is created and will be indicated in the Word document with a comment that notes the link information. If you would like to see this relationship more graphically, click in the right column, then in the <span class="Emphasis">Doc-To-Help</span> ribbon click the <span class="Emphasis">Margin Note</span> button and choose <span class="Emphasis">Highlight Definition Links</span>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <div class="note">
                    <p class="Note-Text" MadCap:autonum="&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #bed230;&quot; class=&quot;mcFormatColor&quot;&gt;Note: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;">This is supported in online outputs only.</p>
                </div>
            </MadCap:dropDownBody>
        </MadCap:dropDown>
    </body>
</html>